 forms and configurations of power, and new practices of nationalism. The history of this community was marked by an unexpected explosion of locally executed violence by the few, which functioned as a generative force in transforming the identities, relations, and lives of the many. The story of this largely unknown Balkan community in 1941 provides a powerful means through which to rethink fundamental assumptions about the interrelationships among ethnicity, nationalism, and violence, both during World War II and more broadly throughout the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aWorld War, 1939-1945 - Bosnia and Herzegovina. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zBosnia and Herzegovina. 4aHistory. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aWest European History.  aviolence, ethnic violence, WWII, Bosnia, Croatia, Kulen Vakuf, nationalism, power.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170588540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501705885423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501705885/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles